# Query & Data Fetching Optimization

## Core Principle

Every query should minimize: **rows scanned**, **columns returned**, **round trips to DB/external services**.
Before writing any data-fetching code, ask:
1. Can I push this filter/sort/limit to the DB instead of doing it in Java?
2. Am I fetching data I already have from a previous step?
3. Can I combine multiple queries into one?
4. Am I fetching 500 rows when I only need 10?

## Rule 1: Filter, Sort, and Limit in the Database — Not in Java

Never load a large result set and trim it in-memory.

```java
// ❌ Fetches all rows, filters in Java
List<PreShiftCheck> all = repository.findAll();
List<PreShiftCheck> filtered = all.stream()
        .filter(p -> p.getShiftCode() == ShiftCode.M)
        .limit(10)
        .toList();

// ✅ DB does the work
List<PreShiftCheck> filtered = repository.findTop10ByShiftCode(ShiftCode.M);
```

This includes LIMIT — if the API has a `limit` parameter, push it to the SQL query, not `stream().limit()` on a full result set.

## Rule 2: Don't Fetch Data You Already Have

If a previous step already loaded entity X, don't query the same table again to get X's fields.

```java
// ❌ Step 1 loads PreShiftCheck, Step 2 queries the same table for IDs
PreShiftCheck pc = preShiftCheckRepository.getById(id);
List<Long> siblingIds = preShiftCheckRepository.findIdsByStudioAndShift(pc.getStudioId(), pc.getShiftCode());
long total = employeeReadinessRepository.countByPreShiftCheckIdIn(siblingIds);

// ✅ Use the entity's fields directly in a JOIN query — skip the intermediate ID lookup
long total = employeeReadinessRepository.countTotalForStudioShift(
        pc.getStudioId(), pc.getShiftCode(), pc.getRosterDate());
```

**Real example from this project:** `buildSummary` was doing 3 queries (find sibling IDs → count total → count by status). Fixed to 2 queries by joining on `preShiftCheck.studioId/shiftCode/rosterDate` directly.

## Rule 3: Scope External Service Calls to What You Actually Need

When calling external services (EIS, roster), only request the entities that are relevant to the current context.

```java
// ❌ Fetches ALL studios from EIS, then filters in-memory
List<StudioResponseDto> allStudios = employeeServiceClient.getStudios(Collections.emptyList());
Set<String> matched = allStudios.stream().filter(s -> s.getName().contains(query)).collect(toSet());

// ✅ First find which studios matter (from DB), then fetch only those from EIS
List<String> activeStudioIds = preShiftCheckRepository.findDistinctStudioIds(today, statuses);
List<StudioResponseDto> activeStudios = employeeServiceClient.getStudios(activeStudioIdsAsLong);
Set<String> matched = activeStudios.stream().filter(s -> s.getName().contains(query)).collect(toSet());
```

**Real example:** `resolveStudioIds` was fetching all studios from EIS. Fixed to first get active studio IDs from DB, then fetch only those from EIS.

## Rule 4: Prefer JOINs Over Sequential Queries

Don't make Query 1 to get IDs, then Query 2 with `WHERE id IN (...)`. Let the DB join internally.

```java
// ❌ Two queries — find IDs, then use them
List<Long> ids = parentRepository.findIdsByFilter(filter);
List<ChildProjection> counts = childRepository.countByParentIdIn(ids);

// ✅ One query — DB joins internally
List<ChildProjection> counts = childRepository.countByParentFilter(filter);
// JPQL: SELECT c.status, COUNT(c) FROM Child c WHERE c.parent.studioId = :studioId ...
```

## Rule 5: Use O(n) Grouping, Not O(n²) Filtering

When grouping a loaded collection by a parent ID, build an index once — don't re-scan the list per parent.

```java
// ❌ O(teams × employees) — scans full list per team
for (PreShiftCheck pc : preChecks) {
    List<EmployeeReadiness> teamReadiness = allReadiness.stream()
            .filter(er -> er.getPreShiftCheck().getId().equals(pc.getId()))
            .toList();
    readinessByTeam.put(pc.getTeamId(), teamReadiness);
}

// ✅ O(employees) — single pass to build index, then O(1) lookup
Map<Long, List<EmployeeReadiness>> byPreCheckId = allReadiness.stream()
        .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(er -> er.getPreShiftCheck().getId()));

for (PreShiftCheck pc : preChecks) {
    readinessByTeam.put(pc.getTeamId(),
            byPreCheckId.getOrDefault(pc.getId(), Collections.emptyList()));
}
```

## Rule 6: Use EXISTS for Presence Checks — Don't Load Entities

```java
// ❌ Loads entire entity just to check existence
Optional<User> user = userRepository.findByEmail(email);
if (user.isPresent()) { ... }

// ✅ DB returns a boolean — no entity loaded
boolean exists = userRepository.existsByEmail(email);
```

## Rule 7: Batch Operations — Never Loop Single Saves

```java
// ❌ 1000 inserts → 1000 queries
for (StudioEmpId entry : newEntries) {
    studioEmpIdRepository.save(entry);
}

// ✅ Single batch — Hibernate uses jdbc.batch_size
studioEmpIdRepository.saveAll(newEntries);
```

Ensure `spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.jdbc.batch_size` is configured (this project uses 25).

## Rule 8: Use JOIN FETCH for Eager Loading in Queries

Avoid N+1 problems when you know you'll access a lazy association.

```java
// ❌ N+1 — loads reasons lazily per employee
List<EmployeeReadiness> list = repository.findByPreShiftCheckIdIn(ids);
for (EmployeeReadiness er : list) {
    er.getReasons().size();  // triggers lazy load per entity
}

// ✅ Single query with JOIN FETCH
@Query("SELECT DISTINCT er FROM EmployeeReadiness er " +
       "LEFT JOIN FETCH er.reasons r LEFT JOIN FETCH r.reason " +
       "WHERE er.preShiftCheck.id IN :ids")
List<EmployeeReadiness> findWithReasonsByPreShiftCheckIdIn(@Param("ids") Collection<Long> ids);
```

## Rule 9: Select Only What You Need

When you only need a count or a few fields, don't load full entities.

```java
// ❌ Loads full entities just to count
List<EmployeeReadiness> all = repository.findByPreShiftCheckId(id);
int total = all.size();

// ✅ DB returns just the number
long total = repository.countByPreShiftCheckId(id);

// ❌ Loads full entities just to get IDs
List<PreShiftCheck> checks = repository.findByStudioId(studioId);
List<Long> ids = checks.stream().map(PreShiftCheck::getId).toList();

// ✅ Select only the ID column
@Query("SELECT p.id FROM PreShiftCheck p WHERE p.studioId = :studioId")
List<Long> findIdsByStudioId(@Param("studioId") String studioId);
```

## Rule 10: Remove Dead Query Methods

If a repository method is no longer called by any service, delete it. Dead queries:
- Confuse future developers about what's used
- Can mask the fact that a better query replaced them
- Accumulate as tech debt

## Query Cost Checklist (Before Every New Query)

1. How many rows will this scan? Can I add WHERE conditions to reduce it?
2. Is there an index supporting the WHERE columns?
3. Am I selecting `*` when I only need 2 columns?
4. Can I push LIMIT to the DB instead of Java `stream().limit()`?
5. Can I merge this with another query in the same method?
6. Am I querying the same table twice when one query could suffice?
7. Am I calling an external service for more data than I need?
